defaultpush for 
defaultthe acclaimed Trinity Shopping Centre, 
defaultwhich opened
default in 2013. 
defaultIf authorities were to keep 100% of business rates this would
default incentivise
default other areas to invest and support in such projects and enterprises.
defaultIt would also be 
defaultappropriate 
defaultfor
default cities to set their own business rates, as 
defaultwas the case
default prior to 1990. Even within city regions there are diverse and complex economies which would be better managed by combined or local authorities controlling the business rates. This would eliminate 
defaultthe problems arising in relation to a nationally set multiplier and encourage cities to come up with 
defaultinnovative
default approaches to attract and support businesses.
defaultAn additional option could be to impose a retail levy on business units, similar to that introduce
defaultd in
default Northern Ireland on large retail stores. 
defaultThe Northern Ireland Assembly passed 
defaulta new 8.5% local rate on retail outle
defaultts with a rateable value
default above £500,000
default, with the money being reinvested to help local SMEs and other growth targets. This same approach
default could be used in our Core Cities, drawing the benefits from investments into new shopping centres such as the Trinity Centre development in Leeds, and using them to help reinvigorate our local high streets and support local SMEs. 
defaultEmployment Tax
defaultCities are being asked to work hard to support jobs and skills in order to boost the economy and reduce benefit bills. And yet despite this, and the costs incurred by local authorities in attempting to improve this situation, authorities are offered no par
defaultt of the benefits that come from their success in making improvements. A small percentage of devolved finance from either National Insurance or Income Tax would provide local authorities with greater expendable finance to improve employment conditions and 
defaultmeet the needs of their communities that result from greater numbers of jobs i.e. in terms of infrastructure.   
